{
  "doc_id": "32227",
  "text": "Imaging evaluation of the liver parenchyma is performed to detect abnormalities such as steatosis, hematomas and hemangiomas [CITATION_1] . The presence of hepatic steatosis, if in significant quantity, can cause postoperative graft dysfunction in the recipient and liver dysfunction or failure in the donor [CITATION_2] . Although imaging studies using CT and MRI scanning can detect the presence of hepatic steatosis, the accuracy in quantifying the degree of steatosis continues to be a controversial issue [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In this study, the enhanced CT images showed no evidence of space-occupying lesions such as hemangiomas, hematomas and hepatomas in the liver parenchyma. None of the images acquired were unenhanced CT images. However, the CT images obtained on all micropigs studied showed a relatively homogenous enhancement of the liver. Consistent with previous reports which demonstrate that the normal human liver parenchyma revealed the homogenous enhancement [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , our findings might indicate no significant difference between human and micropig images.",
